statement:
Answer the following multiple choice question. Check your answer very
carefully. Your answer will be marked right or wrong (work will not be
considered for this problem).

In the Taylor series of $\displaystyle x \ln(1-x)$ (about the point
\emph{x} = 0), the coefficient of the \emph{x}\textsuperscript{3} term
is

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
A. 1/3
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
B. -1/3
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
C. 1/2
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
D. -1/2
\end{description}

sols:
Recall that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \ln(1-x) = -x -\frac{x^2}2 -\frac{x^3}3 - \cdots,\end{align*}

therefore

\begin{align*}\displaystyle x \ln(1-x)= -x^2 - \frac{x^3}2 - \frac{x^4} 3-\cdots\end{align*}

The coefficient of \emph{x}\textsuperscript{3} term is -1/2 and so the
correct answer is D.
